{
  "The s orbital has what shape?": "",
  "Ring": "",
  "Spherical": "",
  "Dumbbell": "",
  "Cloverleaf": "",
  "The s orbital is a sphere centered on the nucleus. At higher energy levels (2s, 3s, 4s), the sphere gets larger but retains its symmetry. Only 1 s orbital exists per energy level.": "",
  "The p orbital has what shape?": "",
  "Cubic (box-shaped lobes)": "",
  "Spherical (uniform shell)": "",
  "Star (multi-pointed rays)": "",
  "Dumbbell (figure-eight)": "",
  "Each p orbital has two lobes (a dumbbell shape) on either side of the nucleus with a nodal plane in between where there's zero probability of finding an electron.": "",
  "The d orbital commonly has what shape?": "",
  "Pyramid": "",
  "Four of the five d orbitals have a four-lobed cloverleaf shape. The fifth (dz²) has a unique dumbbell-with-donut shape — a dumbbell along the z-axis surrounded by a torus in the xy-plane.": "",
  "How many p orbitals exist in each energy level (n ≥ 2)?": "",
  "7": "",
  "3": "",
  "5": "",
  "1": "",
  "The 3 p orbitals (px, py, pz) are oriented along the three Cartesian axes, mutually perpendicular. Each holds 2 electrons, so the p sublevel can hold 6 electrons total.": "",
  "The three p orbitals are oriented along:": "",
  "The x, y, and z axes": "",
  "The nucleus": "",
  "Random directions": "",
  "Only the x axis": "",
  "The px points along x, py along y, and pz along z. Their perpendicular arrangement explains why molecules like water have specific 3D geometries — the orbitals determine bond directions.": "",
  "As the principal quantum number increases, orbital size:": "",
  "Decreases": "",
  "Stays the same": "",
  "Increases": "",
  "Becomes zero": "",
  "Higher n means greater average distance from the nucleus. The 3s orbital is larger than 2s, which is larger than 1s. This follows from the uncertainty principle — electrons with more energy occupy larger regions.": "",
  "The number of nodes in an orbital increases with:": "",
  "Fewer electrons in the orbital's sublevel": "",
  "Higher energy levels (principal quantum number)": "",
  "More protons within the atomic nucleus": "",
  "Lower energy levels (smaller quantum number)": "",
  "An orbital in level n has (n-1) total nodes. The 1s has 0 nodes, 2s has 1 node, 3s has 2 nodes. Nodes are surfaces where electron probability = 0, and more nodes mean higher energy.": "",
  "How many d orbitals exist in each energy level (n ≥ 3)?": "",
  "The 5 d orbitals are: dxy, dxz, dyz (cloverleaf between axes), dx²-y² (cloverleaf along axes), and dz² (donut-dumbbell). Each holds 2 electrons, making the d sublevel max 10 electrons.": "",
  "How many f orbitals exist in each energy level (n ≥ 4)?": "",
  "9": "",
  "The f sublevel has 7 orbitals with complex multi-lobed shapes. Each holds 2 electrons: 7 × 2 = 14 maximum. f orbitals first appear at n=4, used by lanthanides and actinides.": "",
  "What is a node in an orbital?": "",
  "The center of the orbital": "",
  "Where electrons are most likely to be found": "",
  "A region where the probability of finding an electron is zero": "",
  "The edge of the atom": "",
  "Nodes are surfaces where the wave function (ψ) passes through zero. A 2p orbital has a nodal plane through the nucleus. Radial nodes are spherical shells; angular nodes are planes or cones.": "",
  "What is an orbital?": "",
  "A particle inside the nucleus that contributes to atomic mass and nuclear stability of the atom": "",
  "A circular path electrons follow around the nucleus at a fixed radius as described by the Bohr model": "",
  "A type of energy emitted when electrons transition between two different shells inside of the atom": "",
  "A 3D region of space where there is a high probability (typically 90%) of finding an electron": "",
  "Unlike Bohr's orbits (fixed circular paths), quantum mechanical orbitals are probability clouds. The boundary surface shown in textbooks typically encloses 90% of the electron's probability density.": "",
  "What is a radial node?": "",
  "A flat plane through the nucleus": "",
  "A bond between atoms": "",
  "A spherical shell within an orbital where electron probability is zero": "",
  "The outermost boundary of an orbital": "",
  "The number of radial nodes = n - l - 1 (where l is the angular momentum quantum number). A 2s orbital has 1 radial node (a spherical shell); the probability is zero at that specific radius.": "",
  "What is an angular node?": "",
  "A flat plane or cone passing through the nucleus where electron probability is zero (number = l)": "",
  "The angle of a bond between two atoms as predicted by VSEPR theory and molecular geometry": "",
  "A spherical shell within the orbital where the wave function changes sign at a specific radius": "",
  "A point at the edge of the orbital boundary surface where probability is at its maximum value": "",
  "Angular nodes = l. An s orbital (l=0) has 0 angular nodes. A p orbital (l=1) has 1 angular nodal plane. A d orbital (l=2) has 2 angular nodes. They determine the orbital's shape.": "",
  "What is the principal quantum number (n)?": "",
  "The shape of the orbital determined by the angular momentum quantum number (l = 0, 1, 2...)": "",
  "The number that defines the energy level and overall size of an orbital (n = 1, 2, 3...)": "",
  "The orientation of the orbital in space defined by the magnetic quantum number (ml = -l to +l)": "",
  "The spin of the electron within an orbital that can be either +1/2 or -1/2 in value": "",
  "n determines energy and size: higher n = more energy = larger orbital. n=1 has only 1s. n=2 has 2s and 2p. n=3 has 3s, 3p, and 3d. The number of possible subshells equals n.": "",
  "What is the angular momentum quantum number (l)?": "",
  "The number of electrons in an orbital, which is always limited to a maximum of 2 by the Pauli rule": "",
  "The electron’s speed as it moves through the probability cloud surrounding the atomic nucleus": "",
  "The size of the orbital determined by the principal quantum number that indicates the energy level": "",
  "The number that defines the shape of an orbital: l=0 (s), l=1 (p), l=2 (d), l=3 (f)": "",
  "l ranges from 0 to n-1. For n=3: l can be 0 (3s, spherical), 1 (3p, dumbbell), or 2 (3d, cloverleaf). The letter designations (s, p, d, f) come from spectroscopic terms.": "",
  "What is the magnetic quantum number (ml)?": "",
  "The shape of the orbital described by the angular momentum quantum number (l = 0, 1, 2, 3)": "",
  "The number that defines the orientation of an orbital in space (ranges from -l to +l)": "",
  "Whether the electron spins up (+1/2) or down (-1/2) as described by the spin quantum number": "",
  "The size of the orbital determined by the principal quantum number (n = 1, 2, 3, 4...)": "",
  "For l=1 (p): ml = -1, 0, +1. These three values correspond to px, py, pz orientations. For l=2 (d): ml = -2, -1, 0, +1, +2 = 5 orientations. Total orbitals = 2l + 1.": "",
  "What is orbital degeneracy?": "",
  "When orbitals have different shapes such as s being spherical and p being dumbbell-shaped": "",
  "When orbitals within the same sublevel have equal energy (e.g., px, py, and pz are degenerate)": "",
  "An orbital with no electrons occupying it, which is called a virtual or unoccupied orbital": "",
  "When orbitals break apart under the influence of a strong external magnetic field or ligand": "",
  "In an isolated atom, all three 2p orbitals have the same energy — they are degenerate. In a molecule or crystal field, this degeneracy can be broken, causing energy splitting (key in transition metal chemistry).": "",
  "Why does the dz² orbital look different from the other 4 d orbitals?": "",
  "All d orbitals look the same with identical four-lobed cloverleaf shapes in three-dimensional space": "",
  "It is a linear combination of two mathematically equivalent orbitals, resulting in a dumbbell with a torus (donut) around the middle": "",
  "It is actually a p orbital that has been mislabeled as a d orbital in most chemistry textbooks": "",
  "It doesn’t exist — there are only four d orbitals and the dz² is a mathematical error in theory": "",
  "There are 6 mathematical d orbital solutions but only 5 are independent. The dz² is formed by combining dz²-x² and dz²-y², creating its unique shape. Despite looking different, it has the same energy as the other four d orbitals.": "",
  "What is the relationship between orbital shape and bonding?": "",
  "Orbital shapes determine how atoms overlap to form bonds — s orbitals form sigma bonds, p orbitals can form sigma or pi bonds": "",
  "Only s orbitals can bond because their spherical shape allows overlap in all directions equally": "",
  "All bonds are identical regardless of which orbital types overlap to form the bonding interaction": "",
  "Orbital shapes don’t affect bonding because bonds depend only on electronegativity differences": "",
  "Head-on overlap (s-s, s-p, p-p) forms sigma (σ) bonds. Side-by-side p overlap forms pi (π) bonds. A double bond = 1σ + 1π; a triple bond = 1σ + 2π. Orbital geometry controls molecular geometry.": "",
  "How does a 2p orbital differ from a 3p orbital?": "",
  "Same dumbbell shape but 3p is larger, higher energy, and has one more radial node": "",
  "They are identical in size, energy, and node count because both have the same sublevel type": "",
  "2p is larger than 3p because lower energy levels have more diffuse electron probability clouds": "",
  "3p is spherical while 2p is dumbbell because the shape changes with the principal quantum number": "",
  "Both are dumbbell-shaped (l=1 for all p orbitals). The 3p has 1 radial node (n-l-1 = 3-1-1 = 1) while 2p has 0 radial nodes. Higher n means more energy, larger size, and more nodes.": "",
  "A chemistry student draws the 1s orbital as a flat circle. Why is this incorrect?": "",
  "A flat circle is correct because all s orbitals are two-dimensional rings around the nucleus": "",
  "The 1s orbital doesn’t have a shape because it is the lowest energy level with no defined geometry": "",
  "The 1s orbital is a 3D sphere — representing it as a flat circle loses the spatial information needed to understand bonding": "",
  "The 1s orbital is a cube because quantum mechanics predicts right-angled probability distributions": "",
  "Orbitals are 3D probability distributions. Textbook 2D representations are cross-sections. The actual 1s orbital is a sphere, and understanding this 3D nature is crucial for predicting molecular geometry and bond overlap.": "",
  "A student must determine the total number of nodes in a 3d orbital. The answer is:": "",
  "0 — 3d orbitals have no nodes because the d sublevel is the lowest energy within the third shell": "",
  "2 — total nodes = n-1 = 3-1 = 2 (both are angular nodes since l=2)": "",
  "5 — total nodes equal l squared, so for d orbitals with l=2 the total is 2 squared plus one": "",
  "3 — total nodes equal n, so for the third energy level there must be exactly three nodal surfaces": "",
  "Total nodes = n - 1 = 2. Angular nodes = l = 2. Radial nodes = n - l - 1 = 0. So a 3d orbital has 2 angular nodal surfaces and 0 radial nodes. The cloverleaf shape comes from these 2 angular nodes.": "",
  "A materials scientist uses d orbitals to explain why transition metal compounds are colored. The key orbital property is:": "",
  "Only f orbitals produce color because they have the most complex shapes and largest energy gaps": "",
  "d orbital degeneracy can be split by ligands, and electrons jumping between split d levels absorb specific light wavelengths": "",
  "d orbitals emit light spontaneously without any external energy input from photons or heat": "",
  "d orbitals are always colored regardless of whether the sublevel is split by surrounding ligands": "",
  "In crystal field theory, surrounding ligands split the 5 degenerate d orbitals into higher and lower energy groups. Electrons absorb photons matching this energy gap. The remaining wavelengths give the compound its color.": "",
  "A biochemistry student asks why carbon always forms 4 bonds. The orbital explanation involves:": "",
  "Carbon's 2s and three 2p orbitals hybridize to form 4 equivalent sp³ orbitals, each pointing to a corner of a tetrahedron": "",
  "Carbon forms only 2 bonds because it has 2 unpaired electrons in its ground state 2p sublevel": "",
  "Carbon only has s orbitals available for bonding since its p orbitals are too high in energy": "",
  "Carbon has d orbitals available for bonding which expand its capacity beyond the octet rule": "",
  "In methane (CH₄), one 2s and three 2p orbitals mix to create four equivalent sp³ hybrid orbitals at 109.5°. This explains carbon's tetrahedral geometry and why it consistently forms 4 bonds in organic molecules.": "",
  "A researcher explains that MRI machines detect hydrogen nuclei based on their electron orbital environment. This is possible because:": "",
  "Orbital shapes don’t affect magnetic properties because magnetism depends only on nuclear spin": "",
  "MRI detects orbital shapes directly by bouncing radio waves off the electron probability clouds": "",
  "The shape and density of surrounding orbitals create slightly different magnetic environments for different hydrogen atoms": "",
  "All hydrogen atoms look identical in MRI scans because they all have the same 1s orbital type": "",
  "Electrons in nearby orbitals shield hydrogen nuclei from the external magnetic field. The orbital type (s vs p) and proximity determine the degree of shielding, causing different resonance frequencies — this is the basis of NMR/MRI.": "",
  "An advanced student asks why helium (1s²) is unreactive while hydrogen (1s¹) is reactive, if both use the same orbital shape. The answer is:": "",
  "Helium's 1s orbital is completely filled — a full orbital is low-energy and stable, with no tendency to form bonds": "",
  "Helium has a different orbital shape than hydrogen — a dumbbell instead of a sphere for its 1s": "",
  "Both are equally reactive because they occupy the same s orbital type in the first energy level": "",
  "Hydrogen’s s orbital is larger than helium’s, which is why hydrogen has a lower ionization energy": "",
  "Hydrogen's half-filled 1s¹ gains stability by sharing electrons in bonds. Helium's full 1s² has no energetic benefit from bonding — adding to a bonding orbital is offset by populating the antibonding orbital.": "",
  "A photochemist studies why π bonds absorb UV light more easily than σ bonds. The orbital shapes involved are:": "",
  "π bonds involve side-by-side p orbital overlap with a smaller energy gap to antibonding orbitals, requiring less energy (longer wavelength) to excite": "",
  "π bonds don’t absorb light at all because side-by-side overlap creates a node in the bonding region": "",
  "σ bonds involve p orbitals exclusively while π bonds involve only s orbitals in head-on overlap": "",
  "All bonds absorb the same wavelength because orbital overlap type has no effect on energy gaps": "",
  "Side-by-side p overlap (π) is weaker than head-on overlap (σ), so the π→π* energy gap is smaller than σ→σ*. This means π electrons can be excited by lower-energy UV photons, which is why conjugated molecules absorb in the UV-visible range.": "",
  "A nanotechnology researcher uses quantum dots where electron confinement changes energy levels. As dot size decreases, the relationship between orbital size and energy means:": "",
  "Smaller dots confine electrons to smaller orbitals with higher energy, shifting emitted light toward shorter (bluer) wavelengths": "",
  "Smaller dots emit red light because confining electrons lowers their energy and increases wavelength": "",
  "Larger dots emit blue light because having more atoms increases the energy of emitted photons": "",
  "Dot size doesn’t affect energy because quantum confinement only changes the shape not the levels": "",
  "Quantum confinement forces electrons into smaller regions (smaller 'orbitals'), increasing the energy gap between levels. Larger gap = higher energy photons = shorter wavelength = bluer light. This is why QD size controls color.": "",
  "A student calculates that a 4f orbital has ___ total nodes:": "",
  "4 — total nodes equal n, so for the fourth energy level there must be exactly four nodal surfaces": "",
  "7 — total nodes equal the number of orbitals in the sublevel, and f has seven individual orbitals": "",
  "3 — total nodes = n-1 = 4-1 = 3 (all 3 are angular nodes, 0 radial)": "",
  "0 — f orbitals have no nodes because their complex shapes fill all of the surrounding space fully": "",
  "For 4f: n=4, l=3. Total nodes = n-1 = 3. Angular nodes = l = 3. Radial nodes = n-l-1 = 0. The 3 angular nodes create the complex multi-lobed shapes characteristic of f orbitals.": "",
  "A forensic chemist uses atomic emission spectroscopy to identify elements in evidence. Each element has unique emission lines because:": "",
  "Each element has unique orbital sizes and energy spacings, so electrons emit photons at characteristic wavelengths when returning to lower orbitals": "",
  "All elements emit the same color because orbital energy spacings are identical across the table": "",
  "Emission has nothing to do with orbitals — it comes from nuclear vibrations releasing thermal energy": "",
  "Only f orbital transitions produce light because they have the largest energy gaps between levels": "",
  "Each element has a unique nuclear charge, creating unique orbital energy levels. When excited electrons fall from higher to lower orbitals, they emit photons with element-specific wavelengths — an atomic fingerprint.": ""
}